body:
### Reason/Context

As of today, Microcks does not support nested fragment spread selection in GraphQL queries. This is a very common pattern that arises quickly when schemas get more complex. 

### Description

Consider the following query:
```graphql
query film($id: String) {
  film(id: "ZmlsbXM6MQ==") {
    ...FilmCoreFields
  }
}
fragment FilmCoreFields on Film {
  ...FilmIdentityFields
  episodeID
}
fragment FilmIdentityFields on Film {
  id
  title
}
```
Today's return is 
```json
{
   "data": {
     "film": {}
   }
 }
```
where it is expected to be:
```json
{
   "data": {
     "film": {
       "id": "ZmlsbXM6MQ==",
       "title": "A New Hope",
       "episodeID": 4
     }
   }
 }
```

### Implementation ideas

We've got this result because - even if we implemented recursion correctly - the nested `...FilmIdentityFields` fragment operates at the same level as `episodeID`. Because we're applying the fragment filter first, only the `id` and `title` are retained in the response. Later on, we try to retain `episodeID` but this one is absent and thus it empties the result.

We must then change this and operate with collecting and flatening all field selections (simple and fragment-based ones) of the same level before applying the retain on result.

## Summary

Two related bugs surface when a GraphQL client sends a query that uses **named fragment spreads** (`...FragmentName`) to a Microcks mock endpoint:

1. **Bug 1 — HTTP 500 on named fragment spreads.** Microcks returns a 500 Internal Server Error for any query that contains a `FragmentSpread` node. Replacing the spread with a semantically equivalent `InlineFragment` (`... on TypeName { ... }`) works correctly.

2. **Bug 2 — Null synthesis for fields not present in the recorded example.** When you work around Bug 1 by rewriting spreads to inline fragments, the query now requests **more fields** than were recorded in the example. Microcks responds with `null` for each of those extra fields instead of omitting them or returning an error. For real-world components that dereference nested objects without optional chaining, this causes frontend crashes that are hard to trace back to the mock layer.

---

## Environment

| Item | Version |
|------|---------|
| Microcks | 1.14.0 (observed; likely affects earlier versions too) |
| GraphQL transport | HTTP POST, `application/json` |

---

## Bug 1 — Named fragment spreads return HTTP 500

### Minimal reproduction

**This query fails with HTTP 500:**

```graphql
query GetExample($id: ID!) {
  example(id: $id) {
    ...ExampleCoreFields
    someSource {
      ...SomeSourceFields
    }
  }
}

fragment ExampleCoreFields on Example {
  id
  name
  status
}

fragment SomeSourceFields on someSource {
  product
}
```

**This semantically identical query succeeds:**

```graphql
query GetExample($id: ID!) {
  example(id: $id) {
    ... on Example {
      id
      name
      status
    }
    someSource {
      ... on SomeSourceFields {
        product
      }
    }
  }
}
```

The only difference is `...FragmentName` (named spread + separate fragment definition) vs `... on TypeName { ... }` (inline fragment). Both are valid GraphQL per the spec and must produce the same result.

### Why this matters

Almost every production GraphQL client (Apollo Client, urql, Relay) generates queries with named fragment spreads. This means any real-world application that uses code-generated queries will hit this bug immediately when pointed at Microcks. The workaround of rewriting spreads to inline fragments requires intercepting and AST-transforming every outgoing query on the client side — a significant burden.

### Client-side workaround (what we had to implement - Not what we want to have)

```typescript
import { Kind, parse, print } from 'graphql';
import type { DocumentNode, FragmentDefinitionNode, SelectionSetNode } from 'graphql';

/**
 * Recursively replaces every FragmentSpread with an InlineFragment,
 * then removes the now-redundant FragmentDefinition nodes.
 * Applied to every query before forwarding to Microcks.
 */
function inlineFragments(queryStr: string): string {
  let doc: DocumentNode;
  try { doc = parse(queryStr); } catch { return queryStr; }

  const fragmentMap: Record<string, FragmentDefinitionNode> = {};
  for (const def of doc.definitions) {
    if (def.kind === Kind.FRAGMENT_DEFINITION) fragmentMap[def.name.value] = def;
  }
  if (Object.keys(fragmentMap).length === 0) return queryStr;

  function inlineSelectionSet(ss: SelectionSetNode, visited = new Set<string>()): SelectionSetNode {
    const selections: SelectionSetNode['selections'][number][] = [];
    for (const sel of ss.selections) {
      if (sel.kind === Kind.FRAGMENT_SPREAD) {
        const frag = fragmentMap[sel.name.value];
        if (!frag || visited.has(sel.name.value)) {
          selections.push(sel);
        } else {
          selections.push({
            kind: Kind.INLINE_FRAGMENT,
            typeCondition: frag.typeCondition,
            directives: sel.directives ?? [],
            selectionSet: inlineSelectionSet(frag.selectionSet, new Set([...visited, sel.name.value])),
          });
        }
      } else if ('selectionSet' in sel && sel.selectionSet) {
        selections.push({ ...sel, selectionSet: inlineSelectionSet(sel.selectionSet, visited) } as typeof sel);
      } else {
        selections.push(sel);
      }
    }
    return { ...ss, selections };
  }

  return print({
    ...doc,
    definitions: doc.definitions
      .filter((d) => d.kind !== Kind.FRAGMENT_DEFINITION)
      .map((d) =>
        d.kind === Kind.OPERATION_DEFINITION
          ? { ...d, selectionSet: inlineSelectionSet(d.selectionSet) }
          : d,
      ),
  });
}
```

This runs in Node.js (Playwright test runner) and rewrites every query before it reaches Microcks. No changes on the Microcks side.

---

## Bug 2 — Null synthesis for fields not present in the recorded example

This bug is a consequence of working around Bug 1. Once fragment spreads are inlined, the forwarded query may request **fields that were not present in the original recording**. For example:

- The recorded example was captured with a minimal integration-test query requesting 10 fields.
- The real application query (after inlining its 5 fragments) requests 40 fields.
- Microcks returns a response with the 10 recorded fields populated, and **synthesises `null`** for the remaining 30.

### Why this is problematic

Returning `null` for fields that were not requested in the original recording is incorrect. The correct behaviours would be either:
- **Omit** the fields (since they were not in the recorded request), or
- **Return an error** indicating no example matches the requested shape, so the caller knows to provide a more complete recording.

Silently returning `null` is especially harmful for nested objects. A component that does `example.realTime.id` will throw `TypeError: Cannot read properties of null` rather than getting a "no match" signal from the mock layer. This is very hard to debug because the failure manifests in the UI, not in the network layer.

### Secondary workaround required

Because of Bug 2, large queries that contain fragments which expose many new fields after inlining cannot be fixed by inlining alone. We had to additionally:

1. Send a **hand-crafted minimal query** (only the fields present in the recording) to Microcks instead of the real application query.
2. **Backfill the missing fields** on the response before returning it to the browser.

```typescript
// Because of Bug 1 + Bug 2, we cannot forward the real GetExample query.
// Instead we send a minimal query that exactly matches the recorded fields,
// then patch the response with safe defaults for fields the FE needs.
const MINIMAL_GET_EXAMPLE_QUERY = `
  query GetExample($id: ID!, $skipSelfLink: Boolean! = false) {
    example(id: $id) {
      id name status createdAt detectedAt description
      selfLink @skip(if: $skipSelfLink)
    }
  }
`;
```

This is a significant maintenance burden: every time the recording is updated with new fields, the minimal query and the backfill logic must also be updated manually.

---

## Expected behaviour

1. Microcks should accept queries that use named fragment spreads and match them against recorded examples using the **resolved field set** (i.e., after expanding fragments), not the raw query string.
2. When a query requests fields that are not present in a recorded example, Microcks should either omit those fields or return an appropriate "no match" / "unknown field" signal — it should **not** synthesise `null`.

---

## Impact

Both bugs together make it impractical to use Microcks for mocking against real production GraphQL clients, since those clients almost universally use named fragments (often generated by tools like GraphQL Code Generator). The current behaviour forces consumers to maintain a non-trivial client-side query transformer and response patcher — work that should not be necessary.

### Reason/Context

While reviewing the codebase, I noticed explicit `TODO` comments in the Angular frontend codebase suggesting the use of `zone.runOutsideAngular()`. 

Currently, asynchronous timers (`setInterval` in the Keycloak service and `setTimeout` in the Importers page) are running inside the default Angular `NgZone`. Because of how `zone.js` patches async APIs, these timers are triggering global Angular change detection cycles across the entire component tree every time they tick, even when the UI doesn't require an update (e.g., during background token refreshes).

**But I am doubtful about its need!!**


### Description

To improve the performance and responsiveness of the web application, we should move these specific timers outside of the Angular zone.

**Locations to fix:**
1. `webapp/src/main/webapp/src/app/services/auth-keycloak.service.ts` (Line ~57)
2. `webapp/src/main/webapp/src/app/pages/importers/importers.page.ts` (Line ~363)

### Implementation ideas

1. **Inject `NgZone`:** We need to inject `NgZone` via the constructor in both `auth-keycloak.service.ts` and `importers.page.ts`.
2. **Keycloak Service (`setInterval`):** Wrap the interval entirely outside the zone since token updating operates in the background and doesn't immediately reflect in the view:
   ```typescript
   this.ngZone.runOutsideAngular(() => {
     setInterval(() => {
       this.keycloak.updateToken(30);
     }, 30000);
   });
   ```
3. **Importers Page (setTimeout):** Run the timeout outside the zone to prevent Angular from tracking the delay, but re-enter the zone to perform the actual HTTP request so that the UI updates when the jobs are fetched:
   ```typescript
   this.ngZone.runOutsideAngular(() => {
     setTimeout(() => {
       this.ngZone.run(() => {
         this.getImportJobs();
       });
     }, 2000);
   });
   ```

### Describe the bug

`GET /api/secrets/search` returns full `Secret` objects without applying the sensitive-data redaction used by the other secret read endpoints.

For non-admin users, `GET /api/secrets` and `GET /api/secrets/{id}` clear sensitive fields before returning secrets. The search endpoint currently skips that authorization check and returns the repository result directly, which can expose fields such as `username`, `password`, `token`, and `caCertPem` to any authenticated user allowed to call the endpoint.

### Expected behavior

`searchSecrets()` should behave consistently with `listSecrets()` and `getSecret()`:

- admins can receive the complete secret data
- non-admin users should receive secrets with sensitive fields redacted

### Current behavior

In `SecretController.java`, `listSecrets()` applies `filterSensitiveData()` when the caller is not an admin:

```java
if (!authorizationChecker.hasRole(userInfo, AuthorizationChecker.ROLE_ADMIN)) {
   return secretRepository.findAll(...)
         .stream().map(this::filterSensitiveData).toList();
}
```

`getSecret()` follows the same pattern.

However, `searchSecrets()` does not accept `UserInfo`, does not check the caller role, and returns raw repository results:

```java
@GetMapping(value = "/secrets/search")
public List<Secret> searchSecrets(@RequestParam(value = "name") String name) {
   log.debug("Searching secrets corresponding to {}", name);
   return secretRepository.findByNameLike(name);
}
```

### How to reproduce

1. Deploy Microcks with authentication enabled.
2. Create a secret containing credential data.
3. Authenticate as a user with the `user` role, but without the `admin` role.
4. Call:

   ```text
   GET /api/secrets/search?name=<secret-name-or-pattern>
   ```

5. Observe that the response includes sensitive values from the matching `Secret`.
6. Compare with:

   ```text
   GET /api/secrets?page=0&size=20
   ```

   The list endpoint correctly returns the same secret with sensitive fields redacted for the same non-admin caller.

### Suggested fix

Add `UserInfo` to `searchSecrets()` and apply the same redaction logic used by the other read endpoints:

```java
@GetMapping(value = "/secrets/search")
public List<Secret> searchSecrets(@RequestParam(value = "name") String name, UserInfo userInfo) {
   log.debug("Searching secrets corresponding to {}", name);
   List<Secret> secrets = secretRepository.findByNameLike(name);
   if (!authorizationChecker.hasRole(userInfo, AuthorizationChecker.ROLE_ADMIN)) {
      return secrets.stream().map(this::filterSensitiveData).toList();
   }
   return secrets;
}
```

### Additional context

`SecurityConfiguration` already gates `GET /api/secrets/*` behind authenticated roles, so this is not unauthenticated access. The issue is that users who are allowed to discover secret names can also receive credential values through the search endpoint.

Verified against the current `master` / `1.15.0-SNAPSHOT` code path.
